 Configure and test basic firewall rules to allow or block traffic

step 1:Open firewall configuration tool (Windows Firewall or terminal for UFW).
you can open the firewall configuration tool in windows firewalls and you can open in the terminal for UFW.
-Press Windows + R on your keyboard.
-Type wf.msc and press Enter.
-The window “Windows Defender Firewall with Advanced Security” will open.

step 2:List Current Firewall Rules
Command Used:
netsh advfirewall firewall show rule name=all

step 3. Add Rule to Block Telnet (Port 23)
GUI Steps:
In "Windows Firewall with Advanced Security"
Right-click "Inbound Rules" in left panel
Select "New Rule..."
Rule Type: Select "Port" → Next
Protocol and Ports:
TCP
Specific local ports: 23
Click Next
Action: Select "Block the connection" → Next
Profile: Check all (Domain, Private, Public) → Next
Name: Block Telnet Port 23
Click Finish

step 4:Verify the Block Rule was Created
Command:
netsh advfirewall firewall show rule name="Block Telnet"

step 5: Test the Block Rule
First, enable Telnet client (if not already):
command
dism /online /Enable-Feature /FeatureName:TelnetClient
Test Telnet connection:
command
telnet localhost 23

step 6: Export Current Firewall Rules for Documentation
Command:
netsh advfirewall firewall show rule name=all > current_firewall_rules.txt
step 7: Remove the Test Block Rule
GUI Method:
In "Windows Firewall with Advanced Security"
Click "Inbound Rules"
Find "Block Telnet" rule
Right-click → Delete
Confirm deletion
Command Line Method:
netsh advfirewall firewall delete rule name="Block Telnet"

step 8. Verify Rule Removal
Command:
netsh advfirewall firewall show rule name="Block Telnet"

step 9. Final Test - Confirm Telnet Works Again
command
telnet localhost 23
If Telnet server is running, you should see:
text
Connecting To localhost...
